prompt:
Next up for our solitaire collection is Pyramid, and I want the engine as a clean C++ library before anyone talks UI. C++20, stdlib only, pyramid.h and pyramid.cpp:

    struct Pyramid { /* your representation */ };

    bool pyr_load(Pyramid *g, const std::string &deal);
    bool pyr_exposed(const Pyramid *g, int row, int col);
    bool pyr_draw(Pyramid *g);
    bool pyr_recycle(Pyramid *g);
    bool pyr_remove(Pyramid *g, const std::string &a, const std::string &b);
    bool pyr_remove_king(Pyramid *g, const std::string &spot);
    int  pyr_stock_size(const Pyramid *g);
    int  pyr_waste_size(const Pyramid *g);
    std::string pyr_waste_top(const Pyramid *g);
    int  pyr_state(const Pyramid *g);
    std::string pyr_render(const Pyramid *g);

A deal is 52 space-separated cards (ranks A 2 .. 9 T J Q K, suits C D H S). pyr_load fails unless there are exactly 52 well-formed, pairwise-distinct cards. The first 28 fill the pyramid row by row from the apex — row 0 has 1 card through row 6 with 7, left to right; card (r,c) is covered by (r+1,c) and (r+1,c+1). The remaining 24 are the stock, first token drawn first. Card values: A=1, 2..9 pip, T=10, J=11, Q=12, K=13.

- pyr_exposed: the card is still on the pyramid and both covering spots are gone (row 6 starts exposed). Removed, out-of-range or off-pyramid spots are simply not exposed.
- pyr_draw: top of stock onto the waste; false when the stock is empty.
- pyr_recycle: only when the stock is empty and the waste isn't, and at most TWICE per game; the waste goes back so that drawing repeats the same order as before. False otherwise.
- Spots for removals: "Prc" (row digit, col digit, e.g. "P63") for a pyramid card — it must be exposed — or "W" for the top card of the waste. pyr_remove takes two distinct spots whose values sum to 13 (a king never pairs). pyr_remove_king takes one spot holding a king. Anything else: false, no change.
- pyr_state: 1 (won) the moment the pyramid is empty — leftover stock is irrelevant; 2 (stuck) when it isn't won, the stock is empty, no recycle remains (or the waste is empty), and no removal is possible among the exposed cards and the waste top; 0 otherwise.
- pyr_render: 7 lines, one per row, each ending '\n'. Row r is indented by 2*(6-r) spaces; the r+1 entries are two-character cards joined by two spaces; removed cards render as --.

test_pyramid.cpp pins two full deals: one played to the win (including four waste pairings) and one that can only cycle the stock — draw counts, waste tops, both recycles and the stuck verdict are all exact. Every string was checked against an independent implementation. make test is the gate; test_pyramid.cpp, mintest.h and the Makefile don't change.
